Home Price Modeling in Mecklenburg County, NC

Rebekah Adams & Jack Rummler

2022-10-14

1 Introduction

Companies like Zillow attempt to leverage data about city-wide characteristics, public services, and spatial processes to predict and model home price data. In this project, we are attempting to create a model that can capture the dynamics and interconnected relationships between those data to predict housing prices in comparison to actual price for a particular housing market, in this case, Mecklenburg County, NC. The purpose of this is to create a model that successfully captures the attributes that contribute to why or why not someone would be willing to purchase a house in a particular region given various internal and external characteristics.

Home price modelling using machine learning is important for several different stakeholders - for Zillow, building an accurate and generalizable model builds trust for home buyers in the company that they can find a house anywhere within their budget and know the predicted price will be close to the actual price. Accuracy and generalizability (meaning predicted price and observed price is close to 0, and the model is useful for predicting new data with similar attributes and dynamics), are essential components to the model. However, this can be a challenging process, given that we are limited to only our domain knowledge of what predicts house prices and the confines of what data already exists. We often only add indicators that we perceive as necessary to the model, but more helpful indicators may exist that we do not know. While we can engineer features to our model, we may have biases about the features given our domain knowledge. However, even if we had infinite knowledge, no model could perfectly predict house prices.

Our overall modelling strategy is to leverage the domain knowledge we have, and engineer more features based on given data and open source data to manipulate our model. We placed value on indicators we thought people factor into their decision, such as distance to crime, school districts, and environmental conditions, and also factored in the internal aspects of a house people may look for in their decision making processes. Our results indicate that our model explains 73% of variation and was wrong 23% of the time.

2 Methodology

We use a hedonic home price model, where we deconstructed components like internal characteristics (attributes of the infrastructure and features of the home itself), amenities (access to public services and (dis)amenities), and spatial processes (how other houses in spatial proximity relate to each other in price), to inform our model.

We wrangled data from an existing data set that provided the internal characteristics of a home and cleaned up the data to use the necessary indicators that we felt were useful for home price modelling. We then introduced our own data from open data sources based on external characteristics and did an exploratory analysis. The datasets we added were on lakes and water bodies, crime events, school districts, floodplains, historic districts, neighborhood characteristics, and poverty. These came from open data in Charlotte, Mecklenburg County, and the census. We chose this data in particular because based on our domain knowledge, we felt these would help our model, or we could feature engineer them to manipulate our model. We completed feature engineering to help create indicators based on our existing data that could better highlight patterns in home prices. Examples include how close were the nearest five crime events to the household to understand proximity to crime, performance of school catchment zones to understand value of school districts, and number of internal characteristics (eg. bedrooms, fireplaces) to featurize “fanciness” (eg. McMansion, starter homes).

In terms of our analyzing our results, we split the model into a training and test set to evaluate how our model performs using the training test to train the model and the test set to compare it to. Using a cross validation test, we can understand if our model is applicable to several different scenarios. We repeatedly tested the model with different iterations of the features we already had and engineered to see which ones helped successfully compute the accuracy and generalizability of the model. Using Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE), we analyze the predictive accuracy of our model.

3.1.1 Lakes dataset

raw_lakes <- read_sf("./data/lakes_ponds/Lakes_Ponds.shp") %>%
  st_transform("ESRI:102719")

#filter out the three main bodies of water
lake_norman <- raw_lakes %>%
  filter(feat_type == "Lake Norman")

mtn_island <- raw_lakes %>%
  filter(feat_type == "Mountain Island Lake")

catawba_river <- raw_lakes %>%
  filter(feat_type == "Catawba River / Lake Wylie")

lakes <- rbind(lake_norman, mtn_island, catawba_river)

# calculate number of bodies of water within a half mile of each house
data$lakes <- data %>%
  st_buffer(1320*2) %>% # half mile buffer
  aggregate(mutate(lakes, counter = 1) %>% select(counter),., sum) %>%
  pull(counter)

#try with quarter mile buffer, see if correlation is stronger - it is.
data$qmilakes <- data %>%
  st_buffer(1320) %>% # quarter mile buffer
  aggregate(mutate(lakes, counter = 1) %>% select(counter),., sum) %>%
  pull(counter)

# add column to label each home - whether it is waterfront or not
data <- data %>%
  mutate(waterfront = case_when( #half mile from lake
    is.na(lakes) ~ "NOT_WATERFRONT",
    is.numeric(lakes) ~ "WATERFRONT"),
    
    qmiwaterfront = case_when( #quarter mile from lake
      is.na(qmilakes) ~ "NOT_WATERFRONT",
      is.numeric(qmilakes) ~ "WATERFRONT"))

lakes_union <- lakes %>%
  st_union()

data <- data %>%
  mutate(lakes_dist = st_distance(data, lakes_union))

units(data$lakes_dist) <- "ft"

3.1.4 Feature Engineering

data2 <- data2 %>%
  mutate(
    mcmansion = (ifelse(
      actype == "AC-CENTRAL" &
        heatedarea > 2000 &
        numfirepla > 1 &
    #    ((heatedarea/(totalac*43560)) > 0.7) & #ratio of living area to total acreage (converted into sqft)
     #   totalac > 0.5 &
        yearbuilt > 1980 & yearbuilt < 2009,
       "MCMANSION",
      "NOT_MCMANSION")),
    
    old_mansion = (ifelse(
      numfirepla > 3 &
        yearbuilt < 1930 &
        heatedarea > 2000,
      "OLD_MANSION",
      "NOT_OLD_MANSION")),
    
    house_vintage = case_when(
      yearbuilt < 1900 ~ "OLD",
      yearbuilt >= 1900 & yearbuilt < 2000 ~ "20C",
      yearbuilt >= 2000  ~ "NEW"),
    
    modmansion = ifelse(
      actype == "AC=CENTRAL" &
        heatedarea > 3000 &
        numfirepla > 4 &
       # totalac > 5 &
        yearbuilt > 1950,
      "MODMANSION",
      "NOT_MODMANSION"),
    
    fixer_upper = ifelse( # fixer-uppers - would be great to add schools to this
      bldggrade == "FAIR" & yearbuilt < 1930 & numfirepla > 1 & bedrooms > 3,
      "FIXER_UPPER",
      "NOT_FIXER_UPPER"),
    
    starter_house = ifelse(
      bedrooms == 2 & heatedarea < 1500 & fullbaths < 2 & units == 1, #& totalac < 0.6,
      "STARTER_HOUSE", "NOT_STARTER_HOUSE"),

      street_dir = case_when(
        is.na(stdir) ~ "NONE",
        stdir == "E" ~ "E",
        stdir == "N" ~ "N",
        stdir == "S" ~ "S",
        stdir == "W" ~ "W"),

    in_floodplain = case_when(
      STATUS == "EFFECTIVE" ~ "YES",
      is.na(STATUS) ~ "NO"),

    in_histdist = case_when(
      OBJECTID >= 8 ~ "HISTORIC_DISTRICT",
      is.na(OBJECTID) ~ "NOT_HISTORIC_DISTRICT"),

    historic_home = ifelse(
      yearbuilt <= 1950 &
      OBJECTID >= 8,
      "HISTORIC_HOME",
      "NOT_HISTORIC_HOME"),
      
    building_cde = case_when(
      cdebuildin == "62" ~ "62",
      cdebuildin == "01" ~ "01",
      cdebuildin == "01T" ~ "OTHER",
      cdebuildin == "05" ~ "OTHER",
      cdebuildin == "08" ~ "OTHER",
      cdebuildin == "69" ~ "OTHER"),

    stories = case_when(
      storyheigh == "1 STORY" ~ "1",
      storyheigh == "1.5 STORY" ~ "1",
      storyheigh == "2.0 STORY" ~ "2",
      storyheigh == "2.5 STORY" ~ "3",
      storyheigh == "3.0 STORY" ~ "3",
      storyheigh == ">=4.0 STORY" ~ "4+",
      storyheigh == "BI-LEVEL" ~ "OTHER",
      storyheigh == "CAPE COD" ~ "OTHER",
      storyheigh == "RANCH W/BSMT" ~ "OTHER",
      storyheigh == "SPLIT LEVEL" ~ "OTHER"))

# Average price of K Nearest Neighbors
coords <- st_coordinates(data2)
neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords, 5))
spatialweights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")
data2$nnprice <- lag.listw(spatialweights, data2$price)

4.2 Correlation Matrix

The darker the shade of blue or yellow, the more a correlation exists. Crime data (both in nearest neighbors and buffers) has a strong positive correlation, among other features (eg. heated area and full baths). Negatively correlated variables include distance to lakes and nearest neighbor crime incidents, as well as several of the indicators’ relationships to poverty at a census tract level.

4.3 Home prices scatterplots

From these scatter plots, we see nearest neighbor price has a significantly positive correlation to price, crime nearest neighbor 5 has a somewhat positive correlation to price, distance to lakes has almost no correlation to price, and population poverty rate within the census tract the home belongs to has a somewhat negative correlation to price.

4.6 Map 2 - 100 Year Floodplain

This data show whether a house is located in a 100 year floodplain. On its own, the floodplain map is quite uninteresting because there is no surprise that proximity to a water body places a house at greater risk of a flood event. Thus, contextualizing with sale prices for houses in the floodplain helps visualize whether or not being in a floodplain reduces home price value. This map makes it seem like house price value is not impacted by floodplains, which could be true. Floodplains historically reduce property value, and flooding events have caused house prices to diminish from what they could have been sold for. This visualization may not answer the question of how individual houses in a floodplain are valued against other houses closer by in the floodplain.

data.modelling.Flood <- data.modelling %>%

4.7 Map 3 - School Catchment Zone Performance

The school catchment zone grades are determined by the state of North Carolina and were recently released for the 2021-2022 school year. These maps visualize the grade the school each household is zoned for received. We see increased clustering from elementary to middle to high, and there are some similar patterns among house price and grade received (eg. high valued homes in north and south-central part of the county are also where “A” and “B” schools are). Public school funding is notorious for inequitable distribution of resources, perpetuating wealth dispatity in the education system, so the similar pattern is to be expected.

5 Results

5.1 Training

We split our modelling data into a test and training set. We then trained our model on the training data and tested it on the test data using Ordinary Least Squares regression.

# data$municipali <- factor(data$municipali,
#                           levels = unique(data$municipali))

inTrain <- createDataPartition(

5.1.1 MAE and MAPE Table

This table provides a summary of mean absolute error (MAE) and mean absolute percent error (MAPE) for a single test set.

#I'm not sure what they're referring to as a single test set for MAE and MAPE, but I'll run a regression to predict on the test set, and give the MAE and MAPE for that.

# Using last round's regression to predict prices for test set.

data.test <-
  data.test %>%
  mutate(Price.Predict = predict(reg.training, newdata = data.test), #newdata = data.test)
         Price.Error = Price.Predict - price,
         Price.AbsError = abs(Price.Predict - price),
         Price.APE = (abs(Price.Predict - price)) / Price.Predict)

# Take MAE and MAPE of the predictions test results
test_MAE <- mean(data.test$Price.AbsError, na.rm = T)
  
test_MAPE <- mean(data.test$Price.APE, na.rm = T)

# combine into a new df
MAE_MAPE_table <- data.frame(
  MAE = test_MAE,
  MAPE = test_MAPE)

# create a summary table of the df
MAE_MAPE_table %>%
  gather(Measurement, Value) %>%
  mutate(Value = round(Value, 3)) %>%
  kbl(title = "Mean Average Error and Mean Average Percent Error") %>%
  kable_classic_2(full_width = F)
Measurement Value

5.1.2 K-Fold Cross-Validation

We used k-fold cross validation (k = 100 folds) to crossvalidate our model. The distribution of our mean average errors across the 100 folds is presented below. The distribution is centered around the mean MAE value, which is 81,794.

# set up k-fold cross-validation with k = 100 folks
fitControl <- trainControl(method = "cv", number = 100)
set.seed(825) # reproducible folds

knn_cv <-

# Spatial Lag - calculates the average sale price of k nearest neighbors

coords <-  st_coordinates(data.modelling) 

neighborList <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords, 5))

spatialWeights <- nb2listw(neighborList, style="W")

data.modelling$lagPrice <- lag.listw(spatialWeights, data.modelling$price)

This chart plots observed sales prices as a function of the spatial lag of price. The spatial lag of price refers to the average price of the surrounding houses. The positive slope of the plot indicates that as neighboring houses’ price goes up, the observed sales price also rises. Said differently, houses tend to sell at prices similar to other houses near them.

st_drop_geometry(data.modelling) %>% 
  dplyr::select(price, lagPrice) %>%
  filter(price < 10000000) %>%
  filter(lagPrice < 10000000) %>%
  gather(Variable, Value, -price) %>% 
   ggplot(aes(Value, price)) +
     geom_point(size = .5, color = "#0d0887") + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se=F, colour = "#cc4778") +
     #facet_wrap(~Variable, ncol = 3, scales = "free") +

          y = "Observed Sales Price ($)",

5.2.3 Moran’s I

# Moran's I section:

moranTest <- moran.mc(data.test$Price.Error, 
                      spatialWeights.test, nsim = 999)

Moran’s I statistic is used as a measurement of spatial autocorrelation. Below, the results of permuted Moran’s I are shown in blue, and the actual observed Moran’s I is shown in pink. The actual Moran’s I value is 0.162, which is closer to 1 than the permuted Moran’s I values, which indicates that the model’s errors cluster.

ggplot(as.data.frame(moranTest$res[c(1:999)]), aes(moranTest$res[c(1:999)])) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.01, fill = "#0d0887") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = moranTest$statistic), colour = "#cc4778",size=1) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-1, 1)) +
  labs(title="Observed and permuted Moran's I",
       subtitle= "Observed Moran's I in pink",
       x="Moran's I",
       y="Count") +
  plotTheme()

6 Discussion

Our model explains over 73% of the variance in house prices in Mecklenburg County, making it an effective model. Many of our variables provided key insights into the nature of the housing market in the county: for instance, we saw that proximity to the county’s major lakes was a strong predictor of house prices close to the lakes - but that this predictive power waned with distance. We also saw that the poverty rate of the area around a house had a strong negative effect on house prices - the greater the poverty rate, the lower the average house sale price. Surprisingly, being situated in a floodplain did not appear to be a strong predictor of house prices. Our strongest predictor of house prices was our nearest neighbor price. That is to say, the higher the sales price of a house’s neighbors, the higher the chance a house would sell for a similar price.

In terms of accuracy, our model was moderately accurate with a average percent error of 34%. The average difference between our predicted and the actual observed price was $82,911 across all house price predictions. These inaccuracies appear to be larger for homes of higher values.

In terms of generalizability, our model predicted reasonably well on new data: it was correct in its predictions about 66% of the time. As for generalizability across groups, our model predicted differently for different income groups. In low income areas, our model incorrectly predicted house prices 23% of the time; in areas of higher incomes, it incorrectly predicted house prices 34% of the time. Our area is unfortunately not generalizable across groups, and biased towards areas of higher incomes.

Our errors did appear to be spatially autocorrelated, with a positive Moran’s I and evidenced by the map showing the largest errors cluster in the county’s north, and central-south. This suggests that there is a spatial characteristic at play in Mecklenburg that our model did not take into account.

7 Conclusion and Recommendations

Our model offers Zillow the opportunity to leverage key price indicators and transform them into an effective prediction, 77% of the time. FWe recommend future modelers to improve our forecasts even further by incorporating additional spatial processes, such as incorporating parks, highway access, transit access, and airport proximity.
